05309nam a22006615i 9781478009245DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019046700  a97814780092457 a10.1515/97814780092452doi  a(DE-B1597)552811  a(OCoLC)1137740164  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC00aBL1812.E36bY36 2020 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a306.6095124/21 aYang, Mayfair, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRe-enchanting Modernity :bRitual Economy and Society in Wenzhou, China /cMayfair Yang. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (384 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPart I Introduction -- t1 From "Superstition" to "People's Customs": An Ethnographic Discovery of Key Questions in Wenzhou -- t2 The Wenzhou Model of Rural Development in China -- tPart II religious diversity and syncretism in Wenzhou -- t3 Popular Religiosity: Deities, Spirit Mediums, Ancestors, Ghosts, and Fengshui -- t4 Daoism: Ancient Gods, Boisterous Rituals, and Hearthside Priests -- t5 Buddhist Religiosity: The Wheel of Life, Death, and Rebirth -- tPart III religious civil society and ritual economy Grassroots Initiative, Gendered Agency, and Alternative Economic Logic -- t6 Sprouts of Religious Civil Society: Temples, Localities, and Communities -- t7 The Rebirth of the Lineage: Creative Unfolding and Multiplicity of Forms -- t8 Of Mothers, Goddesses, and Bodhisattvas: Patriarchal Structures and Women's Religious Agency -- t9 Broadening and Pluralizing the Modern Category of "Civil Society": A Friendly Quarrel with Durkheim -- t10 What's Missing in the Wenzhou Model? The "Ritual Economy" and "Wasting of Wealth" -- tConclusion -- tAppendix A Chronology of Chinese Dynasties -- tAppendix B Notes on Currency, Weights, Measurements, and Chinese Romanization and Pronunciation -- tAppendix C Religious Sites Visited in Wenzhou by Author, 1990-2016 -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Re-enchanting Modernity Mayfair Yang examines the resurgence of religious and ritual life after decades of enforced secularization in the coastal area of Wenzhou, China. Drawing on twenty-five years of ethnographic fieldwork, Yang shows how the local practices of popular religion, Daoism, and Buddhism are based in community-oriented grassroots organizations that create spaces for relative local autonomy and self-governance. Central to Wenzhou's religious civil society is what Yang calls a "ritual economy," in which an ethos of generosity is expressed through donations to temples, clerics, ritual events, and charities in exchange for spiritual gain. With these investments in transcendent realms, Yang adopts Georges Bataille's notion of "ritual expenditures" to challenge the idea that rural Wenzhou's economic development can be described in terms of Max Weber's notion of a "Protestant Ethic". Instead, Yang suggests that Wenzhou's ritual economy forges an alternate path to capitalist modernity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aEconomic developmentxReligious aspects. 0aEconomic developmentzChinazWenzhou Shi. 0aEthnologyzChinazWenzhou Shi. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUP Frontlist eBook-Package 2020z978311069631808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Eng